  abstract      = {We present an investigation into the first 500 Myr of galaxy evolution         from the Cosmic Evolution Early Release Science (CEERS) survey.         CEERS, one of 13 JWST ERS programs, targets galaxy formation         from z\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde0.5 to z>10 using several         imaging and spectroscopic modes. We make use of the first epoch         of CEERS NIRCam imaging, spanning 35.5 sq. arcmin, to search for         candidate galaxies at z>9. Following a detailed data reduction         process implementing several custom steps to produce high-         quality reduced images, we perform multi-band photometry across         seven NIRCam broad and medium-band (and six Hubble broadband)         filters focusing on robust colors and accurate total fluxes. We         measure photometric redshifts and devise a robust set of         selection criteria to identify a sample of 26 galaxy candidates         at z\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde9-16. These objects are         compact with a median half-light radius of         \raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde0.5 kpc. We present an early         estimate of the z\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde11 rest-frame         ultraviolet (UV) luminosity function, finding that the number         density of galaxies at M\_UV \raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde         -20 appears to evolve very little from         z\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde9 to         z\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitilde11. We also find that the         abundance (surface density [arcmin\^-2]) of our candidates         exceeds nearly all theoretical predictions. We explore potential         implications, including that at z>10 star formation may be         dominated by top-heavy initial mass functions, which would         result in an increased ratio of UV light per unit halo mass,         though a complete lack of dust attenuation and/or changing star-         formation physics may also play a role. While spectroscopic         confirmation of these sources is urgently required, our results         suggest that the deeper views to come with JWST should yield         prolific samples of ultra-high-redshift galaxies with which to         further explore these conclusions.},
